obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line 4
  line `THE ADMINISTRATORS-GENERAL ACT, 1963`
  line `A CT N O. 45 OF 1963`
  line `[11 th December, 1963.]`
  line `An Act to consolidate and amend the law relating to the office and duties of`
  line Administrators-General.
  line `B E it enacted by Parliament in the Fourteenth Year of the Republic of India as follows: —`
  line `CHAPTER I`
  line `P RELIMINARY`
  line `1. Short title, extent and commencement. — ( 1 ) This Act may be called the Administrators-General`
  line `Act, 1963.`
  line `( 2 ) It extends to the whole of India 1 ***.`
  line `( 3 ) It shall come into force on such date 2 as the Central Government may, by notification in the`
  line `Official Gazette, appoint.`
  line `2. Definitions. — In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires, —`
  line `( a ) “ assets ” means all the property, movable and immovable, of a deceased person, which is`
  line `chargeable with and applicable to the payment of his debts and legacies, or available for distribution`
  line `among his heirs and next-of-kin;`
  line `( b ) “ letters of administration ” includes any letters of administration whether general or with a`
  line `copy of the will annexed or limited in time or otherwise;`
  line `( c ) “ next-of-kin ” includes a widower or widow of a deceased person, or any other person who by`
  line `law would be entitled to letters of administration in preference to a creditor or legatee of the deceased;`
  line and
  line `( d ) “ prescribed ” means prescribed by rules made under this Act.`
  line `CHAPTER II`
  line `T HE O FFICE OF THE A DMINISTRATOR- G ENERAL`
  line `3. Appointment of Administrator-General. — ( 1 ) The State Government shall appoint an`
  line `Administrator-General for the State:`
  line `Provided that nothing herein contained shall be deemed to bar the appointment of the same person as`
  line `Administrator-General for two or more States.`
  line `( 2 ) No person shall be appointed to the office of Administrator-General unless he has been for at`
  line `least —`
  line `( a ) seven years an advocate; or`
  line `( b ) seven years an attorney of a High Court; or`
  line `( c ) ten years a member of the judicial service of a State; or`
  line `( d ) five years a Deputy Administrator-General.`
  line `4. Appointment and powers of Deputy Administrator-General. — ( 1 ) The State Government may`
  line `appoint a Deputy or Deputies to assist the Administrator-General; and any Deputy so appointed shall,`
  line `subject to the control of the State Government and the general or special orders of the`
  line `Administrator-General, be competent to discharge any of the duties and to exercise any of the powers of`
  line `the Administrator-General, and when discharging such duties or exercising such powers shall have the`
  line `same privileges and be subject to the same liabilities as the Administrator-General.`
  line `1. The words “except the State of Jammu and Kashmir” omitted by Act 25 of 1968, s. 2 and the Schedule (w.e.f. 15-8-1968).`
  line `2. 1st March, 1964, vide notification No. S.O. 588, dated 11th February, 1964, see Gazette of India, Extraordinary, Part II,`
  line `sec. 3( ii ).`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-5
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Page 5`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  sourcePage 5
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line 5
  line `( 2 ) No person shall be appointed as a Deputy under this section unless he has been for at least three`
  line `years —`
  line `( a ) an advocate; or`
  line `( b ) an attorney of a High Court; or`
  line `( c ) a member of the judicial service of a State.`
  line `5. Incorporation. — The Administrator-General shall be a corporation sole by the name of`
  line `Administrator-General of the State for which he is appointed, and, as such Administrator-General, shall`
  line `have perpetual succession and an official seal, and may sue and be sued in his corporate name.`
  line `CHAPTER III`
  line `R IGHTS, P OWERS AND D UTIES OF THE ADMINISTRATOR-GENERAL`
  line `(a) Grant of letters of administration and probate`
  line `6. Jurisdiction of High Court for the whole State. — So far as regards the Administrator-General of`
  line `any State, the High Court shall be deemed to be a Court of competent jurisdiction for the purpose of`
  line `granting probate or letters of administration under any law for the time being in force, wheresoever within`
  line `the State the estate to be administered is situate:`
  line `Provided that nothing in this section shall be construed as affecting the jurisdiction of any district`
  line court.
  line `7. Administrator-General entitled to letters of administration, unless granted to`
  line `next-of-kin. — Any letters of administration granted by the High Court shall be granted to the`
  line `Administrator-General of the State unless they are granted to the next-of-kin of the deceased.`
  line `8. Administrator-General, entitled to letters of administration in preference to creditors, certain`
  line `legatees or friends. — The Administrator-General of the State shall be deemed by all the courts in`
  line `the State to have a right to letters of administration other than letters pendente lite in preference to`
  line `that of —`
  line `( a ) a creditor; or`
  line `( b ) a legatee, other than a universal legatee or a residuary legatee or the representative of a`
  line `residuary legatee; or`
  line `( c ) a friend of the deceased.`
  line `9. Right of Administrator-General to apply for administration of estates. — ( 1 ) If —`
  line `( a ) any person has died leaving within any State assets exceeding rupees 1 [ten lakhs] in value, and`
  line `( b ) (whether the obtaining of probate of his will or letters of administration to his estate is or is`
  line `not obligatory), no person to whom any court would have jurisdiction to commit administration of`
  line `such assets has, within one month after his death, applied in such State for such probate, or letters of`
  line `administration, and`
  line `( c ) (in cases where the obtaining of such probate or letters of administration is not obligatory`
  line `under the provisions of the Indian Succession Act, 1925 [39 of 1925]), no person has taken other`
  line `proceedings for the protection of the estate,`
  line `the Administrator-General of the State in which such assets are, may, subject to any rules made by the`
  line `State Government, within a reasonable time after he has had notice of the death of such person, and of his`
  line `having left such assets, take such proceedings as may be necessary to obtain from the High Court letters`
  line `of administration of the estate of such person.`
  line `( 2 ) The Administrator-General shall not take proceedings under this section unless he is satisfied, that`
  line `there is apprehension of misappropriation, deterioration or waste of such assets if such proceedings are`
  line `not taken by him or that such proceedings are otherwise necessary for the protection of the assets.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 33 of 2012, s. 2, for “t wo lakhs” (w.e.f. 1 -7-2012).`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-6
  sectionNo (6)
  orderNo 6
  title `Page 6`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  sourcePage 6
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line 6
  line `10. Power of Administrator-General to collect and hold assets where immediate action`
  line `is required. — ( 1 ) Whenever any person has died leaving assets within any State exceeding`
  line `rupees 1 [ten lakhs] in value, and the High Court for that State is satisfied that there is imminent danger of`
  line `misappropriation, deterioration or waste of such assets, requiring immediate action, the High Court may,`
  line `upon the application of the Administrator-General or of any person interested in such assets or in the due`
  line `administration thereof, forthwith direct the Administrator-General —`
  line `( a ) to collect and take possession of such assets, and`
  line `( b ) to hold, deposit, realise, sell or invest the same according to the directions of the High Court,`
  line `and, in default of any such directions, according to the provisions of this Act so far as the same are`
  line `applicable to such assets.`
  line `( 2 ) Any order of the High Court under sub-section ( 1 ) shall entitle the Administrator-General —`
  line `( a ) to maintain any suit or proceeding for the recovery of such assets;`
  line `( b ) if he thinks fit, to apply for letters of administration of the estate of such deceased person;`
  line `( c ) to retain out of the assets of the estate any fees chargeable under rules made under this Act; and`
  line `( d ) to reimburse himself for all payments made by him in respect of such assets which a private`
  line `administrator might lawfully have made.`
  line `11. Grant of probate or letters of administration to person appearing in the course of`
  line `proceedings taken by Administrator-General. — If, in the course of proceedings to obtain letters of`
  line `administration under the provisions of section 9 or section 10, —`
  line `( a ) any person appears and establishes his claim —`
  line `( i ) to probate of the will of the deceased; or`
  line `( ii ) to letters of administration as next-of-kin of the deceased, and gives such security as may`
  line `be required of him by law; or`
  line `( b ) any person satisfies the High Court that he has taken and is prosecuting with due diligence`
  line `other proceedings for the protection of the estate, the case being one in which the obtaining of such`
  line `probate or letters of administration is not obligatory under the provisions of the Indian Succession`
  line `Act, 1925 (39 of 1925); or`
  line `( c ) the High Court is satisfied that there is no apprehension of misappropriation, deterioration, or`
  line `waste of the assets and that the grant of letters of administration in such proceedings is not otherwise`
  line `necessary for the protection of the assets,`
  line `the High Court shall —`
  line `( 1 ) in the case mentioned in clause ( a ), grant probate of the will or letters of administration`
  line accordingly;
  line `( 2 ) in the case mentioned in clause ( b ) or clause ( c ), drop the proceedings; and`
  line `( 3 ) in all the cases award to the Administrator-General the costs of any proceedings taken by him`
  line `under those sections to be paid out of the estate as part of the testamentary or interstate expenses`
  line thereof.
  line `12. Grant of administration to Administrator-General in certain cases. — If, in the course of`
  line `proceedings to obtain letters of administration under the provisions of section 9 or section 10, and within`
  line `such period as to the High Court seems reasonable, no person appears and establishes his claim to probate`
  line `of a will, or to a grant of letters of administration as next-of-kin of the deceased, or satisfies the High`
  line `Court that he has taken and is prosecuting with due diligence other proceedings for the protection of the`
  line `estate, the case being one in which the obtaining of such probate or letters of administration is not`
  line `obligatory under the provisions of the Indian Succession Act, 1925 (39 of 1925), and the High Court is`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 33 of 2012, s. 2, for “two lakhs” (w.e.f. 1 -7-2012).`
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-7
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Page 7`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  sourcePage 7
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line 7
  line `satisfied that there is apprehension of misappropriation, deterioration, or waste of the assets or that the`
  line `grant of letters of administration in such proceedings is other wise necessary for the protection of the`
  line assets;
  line `or if a person who has established his claim to a grant of letters of administration as next-of-kin of the`
  line `deceased fails to give such security as may be required of him by law;`
  line `the High Court may grant letters of administration to the Administrator-General.`
  line `13. Administrator-General not precluded from applying for letters within one month after`
  line `death. — Nothing in this Act shall be deemed to preclude the Administrator-General from applying to the`
  line `High Court for letters of administration in any case within the period of one month from the death of the`
  line deceased.
  line `( b ) Revocation of grants`
  line `14. Recall of Administrator-General ’ s administration and grant of probate, etc., to executor or`
  line `next-of-kin. — If an executor or next-of-kin of the deceased, who has not been personally served with a`
  line `citation or who has not had notice thereof in time to appear pursuant thereto, establishes to the satisfaction`
  line `of the High Court a claim to probate of will or to letters of administration in preference to the`
  line `Administrator-General, any letters of administration granted in accordance with the provisions of this Act`
  line `to the Administrator-General —`
  line `( a ) shall be revoked, if a will of the deceased is proved in the State;`
  line `( b ) may be revoked, in other cases, if an application for that purpose is made within six months`
  line `after the grant to the Administrator-General and the High Court is satisfied that there has been no`
  line `unreasonable delay in making the application, or in transmitting the authority under which the`
  line `application is made;`
  line `and probate or letters of administration may be granted to such executor or next-of-kin, as the case may`
  line be.
  line `15. Cost of obtaining administration, etc., may, on revocation, be ordered to be paid to`
  line `Administrator-General out of estate. — If any letters of administration granted to the`
  line `Administrator-General in accordance with the provisions of this Act are revoked, the High Court`
  line `may order the costs of obtaining such letters of administration, and the whole or any part of any fees`
  line `which would otherwise have been payable under this Act, together with the costs of the`
  line `Administrator-General in any proceedings taken to obtain such revocation, to be paid to or retained by the`
  line `Administrator-General out of the estate:`
  line `Provided that nothing in this section shall affect the provisions of clauses ( c ) and ( d ) of`
  line `sub-section ( 2 ) of section 10.`
  line `16. After revocation letters granted to Administrator-General to be deemed, as to him, to have`
  line `been voidable only. — If any letters of administration granted to the Administrator-General in accordance`
  line `with the provisions of this Act are revoked, the same shall, so far as regards the Administrator-General`
  line `and all persons acting under his authority in pursuance thereof, be deemed to have been only voidable,`
  line `except as to any act done by any such Administrator-General or other person as aforesaid, after notice of a`
  line `will or of any other fact which would render such letters void:`
  line `Provided that no notice of a will or of any other fact which would render any such letters void shall`
  line `affect the Administrator-General or any person acting under his authority in pursuance of such letters`
  line `unless, within the period of one month from the time of giving such notice, proceedings are commenced`
  line `to prove the will, or to cause the letters to be revoked, and such proceedings are prosecuted without`
  line `unreasonable delay.`
  line `17. Payments made by Administrator-General prior to revocation. — If any letters of`
  line `administration granted to the Administrator-General in accordance with the provisions of this Act are`
  line `revoked, upon the grant of probate of a will, or upon the grant of letters of administration with a copy of`
  line `the will annexed, all payments made or acts done by or under the authority of the Administrator-General`
  line `in pursuance of such letters of administration, prior to the revocation, which would have been valid under`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-8
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Page 8`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  sourcePage 8
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line 8
  line `any letters of administration lawfully granted to him with a copy of such will annexed, shall be deemed`
  line `valid notwithstanding such revocation.`
  line `( c ) General`
  line `18. Administrator-General ’ s petition for grant of letters of administration. — Whenever any`
  line `Administrator-General applies for letters of administration in accordance with the provisions of this Act,`
  line `it shall be sufficient if the petition required to be presented for the grant of such letters states, —`
  line `( i ) the time and place of the death of the deceased to the best of the knowledge and belief of the`
  line petitioner;
  line `( ii ) the names and addresses of the surviving next-of-kin of the deceased, if known;`
  line `( iii ) the particulars and value of the assets likely to come into the hands of the petitioner;`
  line `( iv ) particulars of the liabilities of the estate, if known.`
  line `19. Name in which probate or letters to be granted. — All probates or letters of administration`
  line `granted to any Administrator-General shall be granted to him by that name.`
  line `20. Effect of probate or letters granted to Administrator-General. — ( 1 ) Probate or letters of`
  line `administration granted by the High Court to the Administrator-General of any State shall have effect over`
  line `all the assets of the deceased throughout 1 [India] and shall be conclusive as to the representative title`
  line `against all debtors of the deceased and all persons holding such assets, and shall afford full indemnity to`
  line `all debtors paying their debts and all persons delivering up such assets to such Administrator-General.`
  line `( 2 ) Whenever a grant of probate or letters of administration is made by a High Court to the`
  line `Administrator-General, the High Court shall send to the High Courts for the other States a certificate that`
  line `such grant has been made, and such certificate shall be filed by the High Court receiving the same.`
  line `2 [( 3 ) Any probate or letters of administration granted by the High Court for the State of Jammu and`
  line `Kashmir* before the commencement of the Central Laws (Extension to Jammu and Kashmir) Act, 1968`
  line `shall, after such commencement, be as effective as if such probate or letters of administration had been`
  line `granted under this section.]`
  line `21. [ Effect of grant by the High Court of Jammu and Kashmir. ] Omitted by the Central Laws`
  line `( Extension to Jammu and Kashmir ) Act 1968 (25 of 1968 ), s. 2 and the Schedule ( w.e.f. 15-8-1968).`
  line `22. Transfer by private executor or administrator of interest under probate or letters. — ( 1 ) Any`
  line `private executor or administrator may, with the previous consent of the Administrator-General of the`
  line `State in which any of the assets of the estate, in respect of which such executor or administrator has`
  line `obtained probate or letters of administration, are situate, by an instrument in writing under his hand`
  line `notified in the Official Gazette, transfer the assets of the estate, vested in him by virtue of such probate or`
  line `letters to the Administrator-General by that name or any other sufficient description.`
  line `( 2 ) As from the date of such transfer, the transferor shall be exempt from all liability as such executor`
  line `or administrator, as the case may be, except in respect of acts done before the date of such transfer, and`
  line `the Administrator-General shall have the rights which he would have had, and be subject to the liabilities`
  line `to which he would have been subject, if the probate or letters of administration, as the case may be, had`
  line `been granted to him by that name at the date of such transfer.`
  line `23. Distribution of assets. — ( 1 ) When the Administrator-General has given the prescribed notice to`
  line `creditors and others to send in to him their claims against the estate of the deceased, he shall, at the`
  line `expiration of the time therein named for sending in claims, be at liberty to distribute the assets or any part`
  line `thereof in discharge of such lawful claims as he has notice of.`
  line `( 2 ) The Administrator-General shall not be liable for the assets so distributed to any person of whose`
  line `claims he had no notice at the time of such distribution.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 25 of 1968, s. 2 and the Schedule, for “the territories to which this Act extends” (w.e.f. 15 -8-1968).`
  line `2. Ins. by s. 2 and the Schedule, ibid. (w.e.f. 15-8-1968).`
  line `*. Vide notification No. S.O. 3912(E), dated 30th October, 2019, this Act is made applicable to the Union territory of Jammu and`
  line `Kashmir and the Union territory of Ladakh.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-9
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `Page 9`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  sourcePage 9
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line 9
  line `( 3 ) No notice of any claim which has been sent in and has been rejected or disallowed in part by the`
  line `Administrator-General shall affect him, unless proceedings to enforce such claim are commenced within`
  line `one month after notice of the rejection or disallowance of such claim has been given in the prescribed`
  line `manner and unless such proceedings are prosecuted without unreasonable delay.`
  line `( 4 ) Nothing in this section shall prejudice the right of any creditor or other claimant to follow the`
  line `assets or any part thereof in the hands of the persons who may have received the same respectively.`
  line `( 5 ) In computing the period of limitation for any suit, appeal or application under the provisions`
  line `of any law for the time being in force, the period between the date of submission of the claim of a creditor`
  line `or other claimant to the Administrator-General and the date of the final decision of the`
  line `Administrator-General on such claim shall be excluded.`
  line `24. Appointment of Official Trustee as trustee of assets after completion of administration. — ( 1 )`
  line `When the Administrator-General has, so far as may be, discharged all the liabilities of an estate`
  line `administered by him, he shall notify the fact in the Official Gazette, and he may, by an instrument in`
  line `writing, with the consent of the Official Trustee and subject to any rules made by the State Government,`
  line `appoint the Official Trustee to be the trustee of any assets then remaining in his hands.`
  line `( 2 ) Upon such appointment, such assets shall vest in the Official Trustee as if he had been appointed`
  line `trustee in accordance with the provisions of the Official Trustees Act, 1913 (2 of 1913), and shall be held`
  line `by him upon the same trusts as the same were held immediately before such appointment.`
  line `25. Power of High Court to give directions regarding administration of estate. — The High Court`
  line `may, on application made to it by the Administrator-General or any person interested in the assets or in`
  line `the due administration thereof, give to the Administrator-General of the State any general or special`
  line `directions as to any estate in his charge or in regard to the administration of any such estate.`
  line `26. No security to be required from Administrator-General. — No Administrator-General shall be`
  line `required by any Court to enter into any administration bond, or to give other security to the Court, on the`
  line `grant of any letters of administration to him by that name.`
  line `27. Manner in which petition to be verified by Administrator-General. — No`
  line `Administrator-General shall be required to verify, otherwise than by his signature, any petition presented`
  line `by him under the provisions of this Act, and, if the facts stated in any such petition are not within his own`
  line `personal knowledge, the petition may be subscribed and verified by any person competent to make`
  line verification.
  line `28. Entry of Administrator-General not to constitute notice of a trust. — The entry of the`
  line `Administrator-General by that name in the books of a company shall not constitute notice of a trust, and a`
  line `company shall not be entitled to object to entering the name of the Administrator-General on its register`
  line `by reason only that the Administrator-General is a corporation, and in dealing with assets the fact that the`
  line `person dealt with is the Administrator-General shall not of itself constitute notice of a trust.`
  line `CHAPTER IV`
  line `G RANT OF C ERTIFICATE`
  line `29. In what cases Administrator-General may grant certificate. — ( 1 ) Whenever any person has`
  line `died leaving assets within any State and the Administrator-General of such State is satisfied that such`
  line `assets, excluding any sum of money deposited in a Government Savings Bank or in any provident fund to`
  line `which the provisions of the Provident Funds Act, 1925 (19 of 1925), apply, did not at the date of death`
  line `exceed in the whole 1 [ten lakhs] rupees in value, he may grant to any person, claiming otherwise than as a`
  line `creditor to be interested in such assets or in the due administration thereof, a certificate under his hand`
  line `entitling the claimant to receive the assets therein mentioned left by the deceased within the State, to a`
  line `value not exceeding in the whole 1 [ten lakhs] rupees.`
  line `( 2 ) No certificate under this section shall be granted before the lapse of one month from the death`
  line `unless before the lapse of the said one month the Administrator-General is requested so to do by writing`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 33 of 2012, s. 2, for “two lakhs” (w.e.f. 1 -7-2012).`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-10
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `Page 10`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  sourcePage 10
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line 10
  line `under the hand of the executor or the widow or other person entitled to administer the estate of the`
  line `deceased and he thinks fit to grant it.`
  line `( 3 ) No certificate shall be granted under this section, —`
  line `( i ) where probate of the deceased ’ s will or letters of administration of his estate has or have been`
  line `granted; or`
  line `( ii ) in respect of any sum of money deposited in a Government Savings Bank or in any provident`
  line `fund to which the provisions of the Provident Funds Act, 1925 (19 of 1925), apply.`
  line `STATE AMENDMENTS`
  line `Uttar Pradesh`
  line `Amendment of section 29 of Act no. 45 of 1963. — In section 29 of the Administrators-General Act,`
  line `1963, in sub- section (1) for the words “two lakhs rupees” wherever occurring the words “ten lakhs`
  line `rupees” shall be substituted.`
  line `[ Vide the Uttar Pradesh Act 18 of 2011, s. 2]`
  line `30. Grant of certificate to creditors and power to take charge of certain estates. — ( 1 ) If, in cases`
  line `falling within section 29, no person claiming to be interested otherwise than as a creditor in such assets or`
  line `in the due administration thereof obtains, within three months of the death of the deceased, a certificate`
  line `from the Administrator-General under that section, or probate of a will or letters of administration of the`
  line `estate of the deceased, the Administrator-General may administer the estate without letters of`
  line `administration, in the same manner as if such letters had been granted to him.`
  line `( 2 ) If the Administrator-General neglects or refuses to administer such estate, he shall, upon the`
  line `application of a creditor, grant a certificate to him in the same manner as if he were interested in such`
  line `assets otherwise than as a creditor; and such certificate shall have the same effect as a certificate granted`
  line `under the provisions of section 29, and shall be subject to all the provisions of this Act which are`
  line `applicable to such certificate.`
  line `( 3 ) The Administrator-General may, if he thinks fit, before granting a certificate under`
  line `sub-section ( 2 ), require the creditor to give reasonable security for the due administration of the estate of`
  line `the deceased.`
  line `31. Administrator-General not bound to grant certificate unless satisfied of claimant ’ s title,`
  line `etc. — The Administrator-General shall not be bound to grant any certificate under section 29 or section 30`
  line `unless he is satisfied after making such inquiry as he thinks fit of the title of the claimant and of the value`
  line `of the assets left by the deceased within the State.`
  line `32. Effect of certificate. — The holder of a certificate granted in accordance with the provisions of`
  line `section 29 or section 30 shall have in respect of the assets specified in such certificate the same powers`
  line `and duties, and be subject to the same liabilities as he would have had or been subject to if letters of`
  line `administration had been granted to him:`
  line `Provided that nothing in this section shall be deemed to require any person holding such certificate, —`
  line `( a ) to file accounts or inventories of the assets of the deceased before any court or other`
  line `authority; or`
  line `( b ) save as provided in section 30, to give any bond for the due administration of the estate.`
  line `33. Revocation of certificate. — ( 1 ) The Administrator-General may revoke a certificate granted`
  line `under the provisions of section 29 or section 30 on any of the following grounds, namely: —`
  line `( i ) that the certificate was obtained by fraud or misrepresentation made to him;`
  line `( ii ) that the certificate was obtained by means of an untrue allegation of a fact essential in law to`
  line `justify the grant though such allegation was made in ignorance or inadvertently.`
  line `( 2 ) No certificate shall be revoked under this section unless the holder of the certificate has been`
  line `given a reasonable opportunity of showing cause why the certificate should not be so revoked.`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-11
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title `Page 11`
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes
  sourcePage 11
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line 11
  line `34. Surrender of revoked certificate. — ( 1 ) When a certificate is revoked in accordance with the`
  line `provisions of section 33, the holder thereof shall, on the requisition of the Administrator-General, deliver`
  line `it up to such Administrator-General, but shall not be entitled to the refund of any fee paid thereon.`
  line `( 2 ) If such person wilfully and without reasonable cause omits to deliver up the certificate, he shall be`
  line `punishable with imprisonment which may extend to three months, or with fine which may extend to one`
  line `thousand rupees, or with both.`
  line `35. Payment to holder of certificate before it is revoked. — When a certificate is revoked in`
  line `accordance with the provisions of section 33, all payments made in good faith under such certificate to the`
  line `holder thereof before such revocation, shall, notwithstanding such revocation, be a legal discharge to the`
  line `person making the payment and the holder of such certificate may retain, and reimburse himself in respect`
  line `of, any payments made by him which the person to whom a certificate or probate or letters of`
  line `administration may afterwards be granted might lawfully have made.`
  line `36. Administrator-General not bound to take out administration on account of assets for which`
  line `he has granted certificate. — The Administrator-General shall not be bound to take out letters of`
  line `administration of the estate of any deceased person on account of the assets in respect of which he grants`
  line `any certificate under section 29 or section 30, but he may do so if he revokes such certificate under`
  line `section 33, or ascertains that the value of the estate exceeded 1 [ten lakhs] rupees.`
  line `37. Transfer of certain assets to executor or administrator in country of domicile for`
  line `distribution. — Where —`
  line `( a ) a person not having his domicile in any State 2 [in India] has died leaving assets in any State`
  line `and in the country in which he had his domicile at the time of his death, and`
  line `( b ) proceedings for the administration of his estate with respect to assets in any such State have`
  line `been taken under section 29 or section 30, and`
  line `( c ) there has been a grant of administration in the country of domicile, with respect to the assets`
  line `in that country,`
  line `the holder of the certificate granted under section 29 or section 30, or Administrator-General, as the case`
  line `may be, after having given the prescribed notice for creditors and others to send in to him their claims`
  line `against the estate of the deceased, and after having discharged, at the expiration of the time there in`
  line `named, such lawful claims as he has notice of, may, instead of himself distributing any surplus or residue`
  line `of the deceased ’ s property to persons residing out of India 3 *** who are entitled thereto, transfer, with the`
  line `consent of the executor or administrator, as the case may be, in the country of domicile, the surplus or`
  line `residue to him for distribution to those persons.`
  line `CHAPTER V`
  line `L IABILITY`
  line `38. Liability of Government. — The Government shall be liable to make good all sums required to`
  line `discharge any liability which the Administrator-General, if he were a private administrator, would be`
  line `personally liable to discharge, except when the liability is one to which neither the Administrator-General`
  line `nor any of his officers has in any way contributed, or which neither he nor any of his officers could, by`
  line `the exercise of reasonable diligence, have averted, and in either of those cases the Administrator-General`
  line `shall not, nor shall the Government, be subject to any liability.`
  line `39. Creditor ’ s suit against Administrator-General. — ( 1 ) If any suit be brought by a creditor against`
  line `any Administrator-General, such creditor shall be liable to pay the costs of the suit unless he proves that`
  line `not less than one month previous to the institution of the suit he had applied in writing to the`
  line `Administrator-General, stating the amount and other particulars of his claim, and had given such evidence`
  line `in support thereof as, in the circumstances of the case, the Administrator-General was reasonably entitled`
  line `to require.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 33 of 2012, s. 2, for “two lakhs” (w.e.f. 1 -7-2012).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 25 of 1968, s. 2 and the Schedule, for “to which this Act extends” (w.e.f. 15 -8-1968).`
  line `3. The words “or in the State of Jammu and Kashmir” omitted by s. 2 and the Schedule, ibid. (w.e.f. 15-8-1968).`
obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-12
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `Page 12`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  sourcePage 12
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line 12
  line `( 2 ) If any such suit is decreed in favour of the creditor, he shall, nevertheless, unless he is a secured`
  line `creditor, be only entitled to payment of the amount decreed or ordered by the court to be paid out of the`
  line `assets of the deceased equally and rateable with the other creditors.`
  line `40. Notice of suit not required in certain cases. — Nothing in section 80 of the Code of Civil`
  line `Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), shall apply to any suit against the Administrator-General in which no relief`
  line `is claimed against him personally.`
  line `CHAPTER VI`
  line `F EES`
  line `41. Fees. — ( 1 ) There shall be charged in respect of the duties of the Administrator-General such fees,`
  line `whether by way of percentage or otherwise, as may be prescribed by the State Government.`
  line `( 2 ) The fees under this section may be at different rates for different estates or classes of estates or for`
  line `different duties, and shall, so far as may be, be arranged so as produce an amount sufficient to discharge`
  line `the salaries and all other expenses incidental to the working of this Act, (including such sum as the State`
  line `Government may determine to be required to insure the Government against loss under this Act).`
  line `42. Disposal of fees. — ( 1 ) Any expenses which might be retained or paid out of any estate in the`
  line `charge of the Administrator-General, if he were a private Administrator of such estate shall be so retained`
  line `or paid and the fees described under section 41 shall be retained or paid in like manner as and in addition`
  line `to such expenses.`
  line `( 2 ) The Administrator-General shall transfer and pay to such authority in such manner and at such`
  line `time as the State Government may prescribe, all fees received by him under this Act, and the same shall`
  line `be carried to the account and the credit of the Government.`
  line `CHAPTER VII`
  line `A UDIT OF THE A DMINISTRATOR- G ENERAL’S A CCOUNTS`
  line `43. Audit. — The accounts of every Administrator-General shall be audited at least once annually and`
  line `at any other time if the State Government so directs, by the prescribed person and in the prescribed`
  line manner.
  line `44. Auditors to examine accounts and report to Government. — The auditors shall examine the`
  line `accounts and forward to the State Government a statement thereof in the prescribed form, together with a`
  line `report thereon and a certificate signed by them showing —`
  line `( a ) whether the accounts have been audited in the prescribed manner;`
  line `( b ) whether, so far as can be ascertained by such audit, the accounts contain a full and true`
  line `account of everything which ought to be inserted therein;`
  line `( c ) whether the books which by any rules made under this Act are directed to be kept by the`
  line `Administrator-General, have been duly and regularly kept; and`
  line `( d ) whether the assets and securities have been duly kept and invested and deposited in the`
  line `manner prescribed by this Act, or by any rules made thereunder;`
  line `or (as the case may be) that such accounts are deficient, or that the Administrator-General has failed to`
  line `comply with this Act or the rules made thereunder, in such respects as may be specified in such`
  line certificate.
  line `45. Power of auditors to summon and examine witnesses, and to call for documents. — ( 1 ) Every`
  line `auditor shall have all the powers vested in a civil court under the Code of Civil`
  line `Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), when trying a suit, in respect of the following matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) summoning and enforcing the attendance of witnesses and examining them on oath;`
  line `( b ) discovery and inspection;`
  line `( c ) compelling the production of documents; and`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-13
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `Page 13`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes
  sourcePage 13
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line 13
  line `( d ) issuing commissions for the examination of witnesses.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person who when summoned refuses, or, without reasonable cause, neglects to attend or to`
  line `produce any document or thing or attends and refuses to be sworn, or to be examined, shall be deemed to`
  line `have committed an offence within the meaning of, and punishable under, section 188 of the Indian Penal`
  line `Code (45 of 1860), and the auditor shall report every case of such refusal or neglect to the State`
  line Government.
  line `46. Costs of audit, etc. — The costs of and incidental of such audit and examination shall be`
  line `determined in accordance with rules made by the State Government, and shall be defrayed in the`
  line `prescribed manner.`
  line `CHAPTER VIII`
  line `M ISCELLANEOUS`
  line `47. General powers of administration. — The Administrator-General may, in addition to, and not in`
  line `derogation of, any other powers of expenditure lawfully exercisable by him, incur expenditure —`
  line `( a ) on such acts as may be necessary for the proper care and management of any property`
  line `belonging to any estate in his charge; and`
  line `( b ) with the sanction of the High Court, on such religious, charitable and other objects, and on`
  line `such improvements, as may be reasonable and proper in the case of such property.`
  line `48. Power to summon and examine witnesses. — ( 1 ) The Administrator-General may, whenever he`
  line `desires, for the purposes of this Act, to satisfy himself regarding any question of fact, exercise all the`
  line `powers vested in a civil court under the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), when trying a suit, in`
  line `respect of the following matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) summoning and enforcing the attendance of witnesses and examining them on oath;`
  line `( b ) discovery and inspection;`
  line `( c ) compelling the production of documents; and`
  line `( d ) issuing commissions for the examination of witnesses.`
  line `( 2 ) The provisions of sub-section ( 2 ) of section 45 shall apply in relation to a person summoned by`
  line `the Administrator-General under this section as they apply in relation to a person summoned under that`
  line section.
  line `49. Power of person beneficially interested to inspect Administrator-General ’ s account, etc.,`
  line `and take copies. — Any person interested in the administration of any estate which is in the charge of the`
  line `Administrator-General shall, subject to such conditions and restrictions as may be prescribed, be entitled`
  line `at all reasonable times to inspect the accounts relating to such estate and the reports and certificates of the`
  line `auditor, and on payment of the prescribed fee, to copies thereof and extracts therefrom.`
  line `50. False evidence. — Whoever, during any examination authorised by this Act, makes upon oath a`
  line `statement which is false and which he either knows or believes to be false or does not believe to be true,`
  line `shall be deemed to have intentionally given false evidence in a stage of a judicial proceeding.`
  line `51. Assets unclaimed for twelve years to be transferred to Government. — All assets in the charge`
  line `of the Administrator-General which have been in his custody for a period of twelve years or upwards,`
  line `whether before or after the commencement of this Act, without any application for payment thereof`
  line `having been made and granted by him shall be transferred, in the prescribed manner, to the account and`
  line `credit of the Government:`
  line `Provided that this section shall not authorise the transfer of any such assets as aforesaid, if any suit or`
  line `proceeding is pending in respect thereof in any court.`
  line `52. Mode of proceeding by claimant to recover principal money so transferred. — ( 1 ) If any claim`
  line `is hereafter made to any part of the assets transferred to the account and credit of the Government under`
  line `the provisions of this Act, or any Act hereby repealed, and if such claim is established to the satisfaction`
  line `of the prescribed authority, the State Government shall pay to the claimant the amount of the principal so`
obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-14
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `Page 14`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes
  sourcePage 14
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line 14
  line `transferred to its account and credit or so much thereof as has been found by the said authority to be due`
  line `to the claimant.`
  line `( 2 ) If the claim is not established to the satisfaction of the prescribed authority, the claimant may,`
  line `without prejudice to his right to take any other proceedings for the recovery of such assets, apply by`
  line `petition to the High Court against the State Government and such Court, after taking such evidence as it`
  line `thinks fit, shall make such order in regard to the payment of the whole or any part of the said principal`
  line `sum as it thinks fit, and such order shall be binding on all parties to the proceedings.`
  line `( 3 ) The High Court may further direct by whom the whole or any part of the costs of each party shall`
  line `be paid.`
  line `53. Succession Act or Companies Act not to affect Administrator-General. — Nothing`
  line `contained in the Indian Succession Act, 1925 (39 of 1925), or the Companies Act, 1956 (1 of 1956), shall`
  line `be taken to supersede or affect the rights, duties and privileges of any Administrator-General.`
  line `54. Savings of provisions of Police Acts for presidency-towns. — Nothing contained in the Indian`
  line `Succession Act, 1925 (39 of 1925), or in this Act, shall be deemed to affect, or to have affected, any law`
  line `for the time being in force relating to the movable property under four hundred rupees in value of persons`
  line `dying interstate within any of the presidency-towns which shall be or has been taken charge of by the`
  line `police for the purpose of safe custody.`
  line `55. Order of court to be equivalent to decree. — Any order made under this Act by any court shall`
  line `have the same effect as a decree.`
  line `56. Provision for administration by Consular Officer in case of death in certain circumstances`
  line `of foreign subject. — Notwithstanding anything in this Act, or in any other law for the time being in`
  line `force, the Central Government may, by general or special order, direct that, where a subject of a foreign`
  line `State dies in 1 [India], and it appears that there is no one in 2 [India], other than the Administrator-General,`
  line `entitled to apply to a court of competent jurisdiction for letters of administration of the estate of the`
  line `deceased, letters of administration shall, on the application to such court by any Consular Officer of such`
  line `foreign State, be granted to such Consular Officer on such terms and conditions as the Court may, subject`
  line `to any rules made in this behalf by the Central Government, thinks fit to impose.`
  line `57. Letters of administration not necessary in respects of small estates administered by`
  line `Administrator-General in accordance with certain Acts. — It shall not be necessary for the`
  line `Administrator-General to take out letters of administration of the estate of any deceased person which is`
  line `being administered by him in accordance with the provisions of the Army and Air Force (Disposal of`
  line `Private Property) Act, 1950 (40 of 1950), or the Navy Act, 1957 (62 of 1957), if the value of such estate`
  line `does not, on the date when such administration is committed to him, exceed rupees two thousand, but he`
  line `shall have the same power in regard to such estate as he would have had if letters of administration had`
  line `been granted to him.`
  line `58. Powers to grant Administrator-General letters limited for purpose of dealing with assets in`
  line `accordance with the Army and Air Force (Disposal of Private Property) Act, 1950, or the Navy Act,`
  line `1957. — If the Administrator-General applies in accordance with the provisions of the Army and Air Force`
  line `(Disposal of Private Property) Act, 1950 (40 of 1950), or the Navy Act, 1957 (62 of 1957), for letters of`
  line `administration of the estate of any person subject to the Army Act, 1950 (46 of 1950), or the Air Force`
  line `Act, 1950 (45 of 1950), or the Navy Act, 1957, the Court may grant to him letters of administration`
  line `limited to the purpose of dealing with such estate in accordance with the provisions of the Army and Air`
  line `Force (Disposal or Private Property) Act, 1950, or, as the case may be, the Navy Act, 1957.`
  line `59. Act not to affect Army and Air Force (Disposal of Private Property) Act, 1950, or the Navy`
  line `Act, 1957. — Nothing in this Act shall be deemed to affect the provisions of the Army and Air Force`
  line `(Disposal of Private Property) Act, 1950 (40 of 1950), or the Navy Act, 1957 (62 of 1957).`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 25 of 1968, s. 2 and the Schedule, for “ the territories to which this Act extends ” (w.e.f. 15 -8-1968).`
  line `2. Subs. by s. 2 and the Schedule, ibid., for “the said territories” (w.e.f. 15 -8-1968).`
obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-15
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `Page 15`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  sourcePage 15
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line 15
  line `60. Saving of provisions of Indian Registration Act, 1908. — Nothing in this Act shall be deemed to`
  line `affect the provisions of the Indian Registration Act, 1908 (16 of 1908).`
  line `61. Power of Central Government to make rules. — The Central Government may, by notification`
  line `in the Official Gazette, make rules as to the terms and conditions on which letters of administration may`
  line `be granted to Consular Officers under section 56.`
  line `62. Power of State Government to make rules. — ( 1 ) The State Government may, by notification in`
  line `the Official Gazette, make rules for carrying out the purposes of this Act, and for regulating the`
  line `proceedings of the Administrator-General.`
  line `( 2 ) In particular, and without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, such rules may`
  line `provide for —`
  line `( a ) the accounts to be kept by the Administrator-General and the audit and inspection thereof;`
  line `( b ) the safe custody, deposit and investment of assets and securities which come into the hands of`
  line `the Administrator-General;`
  line `( c ) the remittance of sums of money in the hands of the Administrator- General in cases in which`
  line `such remittances are required;`
  line `( d ) subject to the provisions of this Act, the fees to be paid under this Act and the collection and`
  line `accounting for any such fees;`
  line `( e ) the statements, schedules and other documents to be submitted to the State Government or to`
  line `any other authority by the Administrator-General, and the publication thereof;`
  line `( f ) the realization of the cost of preparing any such statements, schedules or other documents;`
  line `( g ) the manner in which and the person by whom the costs of and incidental to any audit under`
  line `the provisions of this Act are to be determined and defrayed;`
  line `( h ) the manner in which summonses issued under this Act are to be served and the payment of the`
  line `expenses of any person summoned or examined under the provisions of this Act, and of any`
  line `expenditure incidental to such examination; and`
  line `( i ) any other matter which is required to be, or may be, prescribed under this Act.`
  line `1 [( 3 ) Every rule made by the State Government under this Act shall be laid, as soon as may be after it`
  line `is made before the State Legislature.]`
  line `63. Laying of rules made by Central Government before Parliament. — Every rule made by the`
  line `Central Government under this Act shall be laid, as soon as may be after it is made, before each House of`
  line `Parliament while it is in session for a total period of thirty days, which may be comprised in one session`
  line `or 2 [in two or more successive sessions, and if, before the expiry of the session immediately following the`
  line `session or the successive sessions aforesaid], both Houses agree in making any modification in the rule or`
  line `both Houses agree that the rule should not be made, the rule shall thereafter have effect only in such`
  line `modified form or be of no effect, as the case may be; so however that any such modification or annulment`
  line `shall be without prejudice to the validity of anything previously done under that rule.`
  line `64. Repeal and savings. — ( 1 ) The Administrator-General ’ s Act, 1913 (3 of 1913), is hereby`
  line repealed.
  line `( 2 ) Without prejudice to the generality of the provisions of the General Clauses`
  line `Act, 1897 (10 of 1897), relating to the effect of repeals, the repeal effected by this section shall not`
  line `affect the incorporation of any person holding the office of Administrator-General at the commencement`
  line `of this Act.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 18 of 1983, s. 3 (w.e.f. 26-8-1983).`
  line `2. Subs. by s. 4, ibid., for certain words (w.e.f. 26-8-1983).`
